info.title: pfSense REST API Documentation
info.description:
### Getting Started
- [Authentication and Authorization](https://pfrest.org/AUTHENTICATION_AND_AUTHORIZATION/)
- [Working with Object IDs](https://pfrest.org/WORKING_WITH_OBJECT_IDS/)
- [Queries, Filters, and Sorting](https://pfrest.org/QUERIES_FILTERS_AND_SORTING/)
- [Common Control Parameters](https://pfrest.org/COMMON_CONTROL_PARAMETERS/)
- [Working with HATEOAS](https://pfrest.org/WORKING_WITH_HATEOAS/)

code.description: The HTTP status code that corresponds with the API response.

status.description: The HTTP status message that corresponds with the HTTP status code.

response_id.description: The unique response ID that corresponds with the result of the APIcall. In most situations, this will contain an error code.

message.description: The descriptive message detailing the results of the API call.

data.description: The data requested from the API. In the event that many objects havebeen requested, this field will be an array of objects. Otherwise, it will only returnthe single object requested.

_links.description: An array of links to resources that are related to this API response.

token.description: The generated JWT that can be used for JWT authentication.

descr.description: Sets a description for this API key. This is used to identify the key's purpose and cannot be changed once created.

username.description: The username this API key is issued to.

hash_algo.description: The hash algorithm used for this API key. It is recommended to increase the strength of the algorithm for keys assigned to privileged users.

length_bytes.description: The length of the API key (in bytes). Greater key lengths provide greater security, but also increase the number of characters used in the key string.

hash.description: The hash of the generated API key

key.description: The real API key. This value is not stored internally and cannot be recovered if lost.

hostname.description: The hostname associated with the ARP entry.

ip_address.description: The IP address associated with the ARP entry.

mac_address.description: The MAC address associated with the ARP entry.

interface.description: The interface where the ARP entry was registered.

type.description: The type of connection this host utilizes.

permanent.description: Indicates whether the ARP entry is permanent in the ARP table.

dnsresolve.description: The full DNS name associated with this ARP entry.

expires.description: The expiration time for this ARP entry.

output.description: The output of the executed command.

result_code.description: The result code of the executed command.

time.description: The time the configuration change was made.

description.description: The description of the configuration change.

version.description: The configuration version associated with this change.

filesize.description: The file size (in bytes) of the configuration file associated with this change.

dry_run.description: Run through the call but don't actually initiate a shutdown.
Run through the call but don't actually initiate a reboot.

aliasesresolveinterval.description: The interval (in seconds) at which to resolve hostnames in aliases.

checkaliasesurlcert.description: Check the certificate of URLs used in aliases.

name.description: Sets the name for the alias. This name must be unique from all other aliases.

type.description: Sets the type of alias this object will be. This directly impacts what values can be specified in the `address` field.

descr.description: Sets a description to help specify the purpose or contents of the alias.

address.description: Sets the host, network or port entries for the alias. When `type` is set to `host`, each entry must be a valid IP address or FQDN. When `type` is set to `network`, each entry must be a valid network CIDR or FQDN. When `type` is set to `port`, each entry must be a valid port or port range. You may also specify an existing alias's `name` as an entry to created nested aliases.

detail.description: Sets descriptions for each alias `address`. Values must match the order of the `address` value it relates to. For example, the first value specified here is the description for the first value specified in the `address` field. This value cannot contain

applied.description: Displays `true` when all firewall changes are applied and there are no pending changes left.Displays `false` when there are pending firewall changes that have not been applied.

pending_subsystems.description: Displays the specific firewall subsystems that have pending changes.

interface.description: The interface this 1:1 NAT mapping applies to.

nobinat.description: Exclude traffic matching this mapping from a later, more general, mapping.

natreflection.description: Enables or disables NAT reflection for traffic matching this mapping. Set to `null` to use the system default.

ipprotocol.description: The IP version this mapping applies to.

external.description: The external IP address or interface for the 1:1 mapping. Valid value options are: an IP address. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

source.description: The source IP address or subnet that traffic must match to apply this mapping. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, `any`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

destination.description: The destination IP address or subnet that traffic must match to apply this mapping. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

descr.description: A description for this 1:1 NAT mapping

interface.description: The interface on which traffic is matched as it exits the firewall. In most cases this is a WAN-type or another externally-connected interface.

protocol.description: The protocol this rule should match. Use `null` for any protocol.

nonat.description: Do not NAT traffic matching this rule.

nosync.description: Do not sync this rule to HA peers.

source.description: The source network this rule should match. Valid value options are: an existing interface, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `(self)`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

source_port.description: The source port this rule should match. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

destination.description: The destination network this rule should match. Valid value options are: an existing interface, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

destination_port.description: The destination port this rule should match. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

target.description:
The target network traffic matching this rule should be translated to. Valid value options are: an IP address, an existing alias. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

target_subnet.description:
The subnet bits for the assigned `target`. This field is only applicable if `target` is set to an IP address. This has no affect for alias or interface `targets`.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

nat_port.description:
The external source port or port range used for rewriting the original source port on connections matching the rule. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `static_nat_port` must be equal to `false`
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

static_nat_port.description:
Do not rewrite source port for traffic matching this rule.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

poolopts.description:
The pool option used to load balance external IP mapping when `target` is set to a subnet or alias of many addresses. Set to `null` to revert to the system default.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

source_hash_key.description:
The key that is fed to the hashing algorithm in hex format. This must be a 16 byte (32 character) hex string prefixed with `0x`. If a value is not provided, one will automatically be generated

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `poolopts` must be equal to `'source-hash'`
- `nonat` must be equal to `false`

descr.description: A description for the outbound NAT mapping.

mode.description: The outbound NAT mode to assign this system. Set to `automatic` to have this system automatically generate NAT rules this firewall, `hybrid` to automatically generate NAT rules AND allow manual outbound NAT mappings to be assigned, `manual` to prevent the system from automatically generating NAT rules and only allow manual outbound NAT mappings, or `disabled` to disable outbound NAT on this system entirely.

interface.description: The interface this port forward rule applies to.

ipprotocol.description: The IP protocol this port forward rule should match.

protocol.description: The IP/transport protocol this port forward rule should match.

source.description: The source address this port forward rule applies to. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `(self)`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

source_port.description:
The source port this port forward rule applies to. Set to `null` to allow any source port. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be one of [ tcp, udp, tcp/udp ]

destination.description: The destination address this rule applies to. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `(self)`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

destination_port.description:
The destination port this port forward rule applies to. Set to `null` to allow any destination port. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be one of [ tcp, udp, tcp/udp ]

target.description: The IP address or alias of the internal host to forward matching traffic to.

local_port.description:
The port on the internal host to forward matching traffic to. In most cases, this must match the `destination_port` value. In the event that the `desintation_port` is a range, this value should be the first value in that range. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, an existing port type firewall alias

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be one of [ tcp, udp, tcp/udp ]

nordr.description: Disables redirection for traffic matching this rule.

nosync.description: Prevents this port forward rule from being synced to non-primary CARP members.

descr.description: A description for this port forward rule.

natreflection.description: The NAT reflection mode to use for traffic matching this port forward rule. Set to `null` to use the system default.

associated_rule_id.description: The associated firewall rule mode. Use an empty string to require a separate firewall rule to be created to pass traffic matching this port forward rule. Use `new` to create a new associated firewall rule to pass traffic matching this port forward rule. Use `pass` to automatically pass traffic matching this port forward rule without the need for a firewall rule. Otherwise, you can specify the `associated_rule_id` of an existing firewall rule to associate with this port forward rule.

created_time.description: The unix timestamp of when this port forward rule was original created.

created_by.description: The username and IP of the user who originally created this port forward rule.

updated_time.description: The unix timestamp of when this port forward rule was original created.

updated_by.description: The username and IP of the user who last updated this port forward rule.

type.description: The action to take against traffic that matches this rule.

interface.description: The interface where packets must originate to match this rule.

ipprotocol.description: The IP version(s) this rule applies to.

protocol.description: The IP/transport protocol this rule should match.

icmptype.description:
Th ICMP subtypes this rule applies to. This field is only applicable when `ipprotocol` is `inet` and `protocol` is `icmp`.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be equal to `'icmp'`

source.description: The source address this rule applies to. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `(self)`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

source_port.description:
The source port this rule applies to. Set to `null` to allow any source port. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be one of [ tcp, udp, tcp/udp ]

destination.description: The destination address this rule applies to. Valid value options are: an existing interface, an IP address, a subnet CIDR, an existing alias, `any`, `(self)`, `l2tp`, `pppoe`. The context of this address can be inverted by prefixing the value with `!`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

destination_port.description:
The destination port this rule applies to. Set to `null` to allow any destination port. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number, a TCP/UDP port range separated by `:`, an existing port type firewall alias

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be one of [ tcp, udp, tcp/udp ]

descr.description: A description detailing the purpose or justification of this firewall rule.

disabled.description: Enable or disable this firewall rule.

log.description: Enable or disable logging of traffic that matches this rule.

tag.description: A packet matching this rule can be marked and this mark used to match on other NAT/filter rules. It is called

statetype.description: The state mechanism to use for this firewall rule.

tcp_flags_out_of.description:
The TCP flags that can be set for this rule to match.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `tcp_flags_any` must be equal to `false`

tcp_flags_set.description:
The TCP flags that must be set for this rule to match.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `tcp_flags_any` must be equal to `false`

gateway.description: The gateway traffic matching this rule will be routed to. Set to `null` to use default.

sched.description: The name of an existing firewall schedule to assign to this firewall rule.

dnpipe.description: The name of the traffic shaper limiter pipe or queue to use for incoming traffic.

pdnpipe.description: The name of the traffic shaper limiter pipe or queue to use for outgoing traffic.

defaultqueue.description: The name of the traffic shaper queue to assume as the default queue for traffic matching this rule.

ackqueue.description: The name of the traffic shaper queue to assume as the ACK queue for ACK traffic matching this rule.

floating.description: Mark this rule as a floating firewall rule.

quick.description:
Apply this action to traffic that matches this rule immediately. This field only applies to floating firewall rules.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `floating` must be equal to `true`

direction.description:
The direction of traffic this firewall rule applies to. This field only applies to floating firewall rules.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `floating` must be equal to `true`

tracker.description: The internal tracking ID for this firewall rule.

associated_rule_id.description: The internal rule ID for the NAT rule associated with this rule.

created_time.description: The unix timestamp of when this firewall rule was original created.

created_by.description: The username and IP of the user who originally created this firewall rule.

updated_time.description: The unix timestamp of when this firewall rule was original created.

updated_by.description: The username and IP of the user who last updated this firewall rule.

schedlabel.description: A unique ID for this schedule used internally by the system.

name.description: The unique name to assign this schedule.

descr.description: A description of this schedules purpose.

active.description: Displays whether the schedule is currently active or not.

timerange.description: The date/times this firewall schedule will be active.

position.description: The day of the week this schedule should be active for. Use `1` for every Monday, `2` for every Tuesday, `3` for every Wednesday, `4` for every Thursday, `5` for every Friday, `6` for every Saturday, or `7` for every Sunday. If this field has a value specified, the `month` and `day` fields will be unavailable.

month.description:
The month for each specified `day` value. Each value specified must correspond with a `day` field value and must match the order exactly. For example, a `month` value of `[3, 6]` and a `day` value of `[2, 17]` would evaluate to March 2nd and June 17th respectively.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `position` must be equal to `NULL`

day.description:
The day for each specified `month` value. Each value specified must correspond with a `month` field value and must match the order exactly. For example, a `month` value of `[3, 6]` and a `day` value of `[2, 17]` would evaluate to March 2nd and June 17th respectively.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `position` must be equal to `NULL`

hour.description: The start time and end time for this time range in 24-hour format (i.e. HH:MM-HH:MM).

rangedescr.description: A description detailing this firewall schedule time range's purpose.

interface.description: The interface that initially received the traffic which registered the state.

protocol.description: The protocol listed in the state.

direction.description: The direction of traffic listed in the state.

source.description: The source address listed in the state. Note: Depending on the `protocol`, this value may contain the source port as well.

destination.description: The destination address listed in the state. Note: Depending on the `protocol`, this value may contain the destination port as well.

state.description: The current status of the firewall state.

age.description: The age of the firewall state in HH:MM:SS format.

expires_in.description: The amount of time remaining until the state expires in HH:MM:SS format.

packets_total.description: The total number of packets observed by the state.

packets_in.description: The total number of inbound packets observed by the state.

packets_out.description: The total number of outbound packets observed by the state.

bytes_total.description: The total number of traffic (in bytes) observed by the state.

bytes_in.description: The total number of inbound traffic (in bytes) observed by the state.

bytes_out.description: The total number of outbound traffic (in bytes) observed by the state.

maximumstates.description: The maximum number of firewall state entries allowed by this firewall.

defaultmaximumstates.description: The default number of firewall state entries allowed by this firewall.

currentstates.description: The number of firewall state entries currently registered in the states table.

enabled.description: Enables or disables this traffic shaper.

interface.description: The interface this traffic shaper will be applied to.

name.description: The name of this traffic shaper. This value is automatically set by the system and cannot be changed.

scheduler.description: The scheduler type to use for this traffic shaper. Changing this value will automatically update any child queues assigned to this traffic shaper.

bandwidthtype.description: The scale type of the `bandwidth` field's value.

bandwidth.description: The total bandwidth amount allowed by this traffic shaper.

qlimit.description:
The number of packets that can be held in a queue waiting to be transmitted by the shaper.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `scheduler` must not be one of [ CODELQ ]

tbrconfig.description: The size, in bytes, of the token bucket regulator. If `null`, heuristics based on the interface bandwidth are used to determine the size.

queue.description: The child queues assigned to this traffic shaper.

bw.description: The amount of bandwidth this profile allows.

bwscale.description: The scale factor of the `bw` fields value.

bwsched.description: The schedule to assign this bandwidth profile. When this firewall schedule is active, this bandwidth profile will be used.

name.description: The unique name for this limiter.

number.description: A unique number auto-assigned to this limiter. This is only used internally by the system and cannot be manually set or changed.

enabled.description: Enables or disables this limiter and its child queues.

mask.description: If `source` or `destination` slots is chosen a dynamic pipe with the bandwidth, delay, packet loss and queue size given above will be created for each source/destination IP address encountered, respectively. This makes it possible to easily specify bandwidth limits per host or subnet.

maskbits.description:
The IPv4 mask bits to use when determine the scope of the dynamic pipe for IPv4 traffic.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mask` must be one of [ srcaddress, dstaddress ]

maskbitsv6.description:
The IPv6 mask bits to use when determine the scope of the dynamic pipe for IPv4 traffic.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mask` must be one of [ srcaddress, dstaddress ]

qlimit.description: The length of the limiter's queue which the scheduler and AQM are responsible for. Set to `null` to assume default.

ecn.description:
Enable or disable ECN. ECN sets a reserved TCP flag when the queue is nearing or exceeding capacity. Not all AQMs or schedulers support this.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be one of [ codel, pie, red, gred ]
- `sched` must be one of [ fq_codel, fq_pie ]

description.description: The verbose description for this limiter.

aqm.description: The Active Queue Management (AQM) algorithm to use for this limiter. AQM is the intelligent drop of network packets inside the limiter, when it becomes full or gets close to becoming full, with the goal of reducing network congestion.

sched.description: The scheduler to use for this limiter. The scheduler manages the sequence of network packets in the limiter's queue.

param_codel_target.description:
The value for the CoDel target parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be equal to `'codel'`

param_codel_interval.description:
The value for the CoDel interval parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be equal to `'codel'`

param_pie_target.description:
The value for the PIE target parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be equal to `'pie'`

param_pie_tupdate.description:
The value for the PIE tupdate parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be equal to `'pie'`

param_pie_alpha.description:
The value for the PIE alpha parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `aqm` must be equal to `'pie'`

param_pie_beta.description:

weight.description: The share of the parent limiter this queue gets.

plr.description: The amount of packet loss (in percentage) added to traffic passing through this limiter queue.

interface.description: The parent interface this traffic shaper queue a child of. This value is automatically determined by the queue's parent and cannot be manually set or changed.

enabled.description: Enables or disables the traffic shaper queue.

name.description: The name to assign this traffic shaper queue.

priority.description:
The priority level for this traffic shaper queue.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be one of [ FAIRQ, CBQ, PRIQ ]

qlimit.description: The number of packets that can be held in a queue waiting to be transmitted by the shaper.

description.description: A description for this traffic shaper queue.

default.description: Mark this traffic shaper queue as the default queue.

red.description: Use the 'Random Early Detection' scheduler option for this traffic shaper queue.

rio.description: Use the 'Random Early Detection In and Out' scheduler option for this traffic shaper queue.

ecn.description: Use the 'Explicit Congestion Notification' scheduler option for this traffic shaper queue.

codel.description: Use the 'Codel Active Queue' scheduler option for this traffic shaper queue.

bandwidthtype.description:
The scale type of the `bandwidth` field's value.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be one of [ FAIRQ, CBQ, HFSC ]

bandwidth.description:
The total bandwidth amount allowed by this traffic shaper.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be one of [ FAIRQ, CBQ, HFSC ]

buckets.description:
This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'FAIRQ'`

hogs.description:
The bandwidth limit per host.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'FAIRQ'`

borrow.description:
Allow this queue to borrow from other queues when available.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'CBQ'`

upperlimit.description:
Allow setting the maximum bandwidth allowed for the queue. Will force hard bandwidth limiting.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'HFSC'`

upperlimit_m1.description:
The burst-able bandwidth limit for this traffic shaper queue.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `upperlimit` must be equal to `true`

upperlimit_d.description:
The duration (in milliseconds) that the burst-able bandwidth limit (`upperlimit_m1` is in effect.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `upperlimit` must be equal to `true`

upperlimit_m2.description:
The normal bandwidth limit for this traffic shaper queue. If `upperlimit_m1` is not defined, this limit will always be in effect. If `upperlimit_m1` is defined, this limit will take effect after the `upperlimit_d` duration has expired.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `upperlimit` must be equal to `true`

realtime.description:
Allow setting the guaranteed bandwidth minimum allotted to the queue.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'HFSC'`

realtime_m1.description:
The guaranteed minimum bandwidth limit for this traffic shaper queue during real time.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `realtime` must be equal to `true`

realtime_d.description:
The duration (in milliseconds) that the guaranteed bandwidth limit (`realtime_m1`) is in effect.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `realtime` must be equal to `true`

realtime_m2.description:
The maximum bandwidth this traffic shaper queue is allowed to use. Note: This value should not exceed 30% of parent queue's maximum bandwidth.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `realtime` must be equal to `true`

linkshare.description:
Allow sharing bandwidth from this queue for other queues as long as the real time values have been satisfied.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- Parent field `scheduler` must be equal to `'HFSC'`

linkshare_m1.description:
The initial bandwidth limit for this traffic shaper queue when link sharing.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `linkshare` must be equal to `true`

linkshare_d.description:
The duration (in milliseconds) that the initial bandwidth limit (`linkshare_m1`) is in effect.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `linkshare` must be equal to `true`

linkshare_m2.description:
The maximum bandwidth this traffic shaper queue is allowed to use. Note: This behaves exactly the same as the `bandwidth` field. If this field is set, it will override whatever value is current assigned to the `bandwidth` field.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `linkshare` must be equal to `true`

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'staticv6'`

gatewayv6.description:
Sets the upstream IPv6 gateway this interface will use. This is only applicable for WAN-type interfaces.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'staticv6'`

ipv6usev4iface.description:
Enable or disable IPv6 using the IPv4 connectivity link (PPPoE).

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'staticv6'`

slaacusev4iface.description:
Enable or disable IPv6 using the IPv4 connectivity link (PPPoE).

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'slaac'`

prefix_6rd.description:
Sets the 6RD IPv6 prefix assigned by the ISP for this interface.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'6rd'`

gateway_6rd.description:
Sets the 6RD IPv4 gateway address assigned by the ISP for this interface.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'6rd'`

prefix_6rd_v4plen.description:
Sets the 6RD IPv4 prefix length. Normally specified by the ISP. A value of 0 means embed theentire IPv4 address in the 6RD prefix.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'6rd'`

track6_interface.description:
Sets the dynamic IPv6 WAN interface to track for configuration.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'track6'`

track6_prefix_id_hex.description:
Sets the hexadecimal IPv6 prefix ID. This determines the configurable network ID based on the dynamic IPv6 connection.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `typev6` must be equal to `'track6'`

applied.description: Displays `true` when all routing changes are applied and there are no pending changes left.Displays `false` when there are pending routing changes that have not been applied.

defaultgw4.description: The gateway to assigns as the default IPv4 gateway for this system. Leave blank to automatically determine the default gateway, or set to `-` to assign no gateway.

defaultgw6.description: The gateway to assigns as the default IPv6 gateway for this system. Leave blank to automatically determine the default gateway, or set to `-` to assign no gateway.

name.description: Sets a name for the gateway.

descr.description: Sets a descriptions for the gateway.

ipprotocol.description: Sets the Internet Protocol version this gateway uses.

interface.description: Sets the interface this gateway will apply to.

gateway.description: Sets the IP address of the remote gateway.

monitor_disable.description: Disable gateway monitoring for this gateway.

monitor.description:
Sets a different IP address to use when monitoring this gateway. This is typically only necessary if the gateway IP does not accept ICMP probes.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `monitor_disable` must be equal to `false`

action_disable.description: Disable actions from taking place when gateway events occur. The gateway will always be considered up.

force_down.description: Always consider this gateway to be up.

dpinger_dont_add_static_route.description: Prevents gateway monitoring from adding a static route for this gateway's monitor IP.

gw_down_kill_states.description: Controls the state killing behavior when this specific gateway goes down. Killing states for specific down gateways only affects states created by policy routing rules and reply-to. Has no effect if gateway monitoring or its action are disabled or if the gateway is forced down. May not have any effect on dynamic gateways during a link loss event.

nonlocalgateway.description: Allows or disallows gateway IPs that are not a part of the parent interface's subnet(s).

weight.description: Sets the weight for this gateway when used in a Gateway Group.

data_payload.description: Sets the data payload to send in ICMP packets to gateway monitor IP.

latencylow.description: Sets the threshold to consider latency as low.

latencyhigh.description: Sets the threshold to consider latency as high. This value must be greater than `latencylow`.

losslow.description: Sets the threshold to consider packet loss as low.

losshigh.description: Sets the threshold to consider packet loss as high. This value must be greater than `losslow`.

interval.description: Sets how often ICMP probes will be sent in milliseconds.

loss_interval.description: Sets the time interval in milliseconds before packets are treated as lost.

time_period.description: Sets the time period in milliseconds over which results are averaged.

alert_interval.description: Sets the time interval in milliseconds between checking for an alert conditions.

name.description: The name of the gateway group.

trigger.description: The trigger that will cause a gateway to be excluded from the group.

descr.description: A description of the gateway group.

ipprotocol.description: The assumed IP protocol of the gateways in this group.

priorities.description: The priorities of the gateways in this group.

gateway.description: The name of the gateway to prioritize in this gateway group.

tier.description: The priority of this gateway in the group. Lower numbered tiers are higher priority.

virtual_ip.description: The virtual IP to use for this gateway group. Use `address` to use the interface's current IP.

network.description: Sets the destination network for this static route in CIDR notation.

gateway.description: Sets which gateway this route applies to.

descr.description: Sets a description for administrative reference.

name.description: The name of the ACME account key.

descr.description: A description of the ACME account key.

email.description: The email address associated with the ACME account key.

acmeserver.description: The ACME server this account key will belong to.

accountkey.description: The RSA private key for the ACME account key.

name.description: The name of the ACME account key to register.

status.description: The registration status of the ACME account key. This will show 'pending' if the registration process is still running, 'registered' if the registration was successful, 'failed' if the registration failed, and 'unknown' if the registration status is not known. Note: This status can only be determined for registrations initiated through the REST API.
The activation status of the ACME certificate.

command.description: The command to execute on the ACME certificate.

method.description: The action method that should be used to run the command.

name.description: The fully-qualified domain name of this domain (SAN).

status.description: The activation status of the ACME certificate.

method.description: The method to use to validate this domain.

type.description: The type of access this entry provides. "allow" entries permit access to the REST API from the specified networks. "deny" entries block access to the REST API from the specified networks.

weight.description: The weight of this entry. Entries with lower weights are evaluated first. If multiple entries match a request, the entry with the lowest weight will be applied.

network.description: The network (in CIDR notation) that this entry applies to. Clients interacting with the REST API from this network will be affected by this entry.

users.description: The users that this entry applies to. Only users in this list will be affected by this entry.

sched.description: The firewall schedule that this entry will use. This entry will only be active during the times specified in the schedule. Leave empty to apply this entry at all times.

descr.description: A description of this access list entry. This field is optional.

enabled.description: Enables or disables the API. If set to `false`, the API will no longer respond to API requests and can only be re-enabled via webConfigurator.

read_only.description: Enables or disables read-only API access. If enabled, the API will only respond to GET requests and can only be disabled via webConfigurator.

keep_backup.description: Enables or disables keeping a persistent backup of the API configuration that can be used to restore the API configuration after package and systems updates.

login_protection.description: Enables or disables Login Protection for API authentication. When enabled, Login Protection will monitor API attempts and temporarily block clients who fail API authentication too many times within a period of time. When disabled, Login Protection will not monitor API authentication but will continue to monitor webConfigurator and SSH logins (if configured). Login Protection can be configured globally in System > Advanced.

log_successful_auth.description: Enables or disables logging of API authentication attempts that are successful. By default, only failed API authentication attempts are logged to prevent flooding the authentication logs. This field is only applicable when the API `login_protection` setting is enabled.

allow_pre_releases.description: Enables or disables displaying pre-releases in available API updates. Pre-releases contain fixes and features that are currently under development and may not be fully stable. Use of pre-release versions is at your own risk.

hateoas.description: Enables or disables HATEOAS. Enabling HATEOAS will allow the API to include links to related resources in API responses. This is primarily useful for frontend web applications and self-navigating client scripts that integrate with HAL standards. Enabling HATEOAS may increase API response times, especially on systems with large configurations.

expose_sensitive_fields.description: Enables or disables exposing sensitive fields in API responses. When enabled, sensitive fields such as passwords, private keys, and other sensitive data will be included in API responses.

override_sensitive_fields.description:
Specifies a list of fields (formatted as ModelName:FieldName) that should have their sensitive attribute overridden. Fields selected here will not be considered sensitive and will be included in API responses regardless of the `expose_sensitive_fields` setting.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `expose_sensitive_fields` must be equal to `false`

allowed_interfaces.description: Sets the interfaces allowed to accept incoming API calls.

represent_interfaces_as.description: Specifies how the API should represent interface names. Use `descr` to represent interface objects by their description name, use `id` to represent interface objects by their internal pfSense ID (e.g. wan, lan, opt1), or use `if` to represent interface objects by their real interface name (e.g. em0, igb1, bxe3).

auth_methods.description: Sets the API authentication methods allowed to authenticate API calls.

jwt_exp.description: Sets the amount of time (in seconds) JWTs are valid for.

ha_sync.description: Enables or disables syncing API settings to HA peers. When enabled, API settings from this host will automatically be synced to any hosts defined in `ha_sync_hosts`.

ha_sync_validate_certs.description: Enables or disables certificate validation when syncing API configurations to HA sync peers. If enabled, all hosts defined in `ha_sync_hosts` must have their webConfigurator configured with a certificate trusted by this system. It is strongly recommended this be enabled at all times to help mitigate Man-in-the-Middle attacks.

ha_sync_hosts.description: Set a list of IP addresses or hostnames to sync API settings to.

ha_sync_username.description: Sets the username to use when authenticating for HA sync processes. This user must be the present on all hosts defined in `ha_sync_hosts`.

ldap_pam_groupdn.description:

ldap_utf8.description:

ldap_nostrip_at.description:

ldap_allow_unauthenticated.description:
Enables or disables unauthenticated binding. Unauthenticated binds are bind with an existing login but with an empty password. Some LDAP servers (Microsoft AD) allow this type of bind without any possibility to disable it.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'ldap'`

radius_secret.description:

radius_auth_port.description:
The port used by RADIUS for authentication. Set to `null` to disable use of authentication services. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'radius'`

radius_acct_port.description:
The port used by RADIUS for accounting. Set to `null` to disable use of accounting services. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'radius'`

radius_protocol.description:
The RADIUS protocol to use when authenticating.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'radius'`

radius_timeout.description:
The timeout (in seconds) for connections to this RADIUS authentication server.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'radius'`

radius_nasip_attribute.description:
The interface whose IP will be used as the 'NAS-IP-Address' attribute during RADIUS Access-Requests. This choice will not change the interface used for contacting the RADIUS server.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `type` must be equal to `'radius'`

name.description: The username of this local user.

password.description: The password of this local user.

uid.description: The UID of this local user. This value is automatically assigned and cannot be changed.

scope.description: The scope of this local user. This value is automatically assigned and cannot be changed.

priv.description: The privileges assigned to this local user.

descr.description: The full descriptive name for this local user.

expires.description: The expiration date for this user in mm/dd/YYYY format. Use empty string for no expiration

cert.description: The user certificates to assign this user. Items must be existing certificate `refid`s.

authorizedkeys.description: The SSH authorized keys to assign this user.

ipsecpsk.description: The IPsec pre-shared key to assign this user.

name.description: The name for this user group.

gid.description: The GID of this user group. This value is automatically assigned and cannot be changed.

scope.description: The scope of this user group. Use `local` for user groups that only apply to this system. use `remote` for groups that also apply to remote authentication servers.

description.description: The description to assign to this user group.

member.description: The local user names to assign to this user group.

priv.description: The privileges to assign to this user group.

applied.description: Displays `true` when all IPsec changes are applied and there are no pending changes left.Displays `false` when there are pending IPsec changes that have not been applied.

encryption_algorithm_name.description: The name of the encryption algorithm to use for this P1 encryption item.

encryption_algorithm_keylen.description:
The key length for the encryption algorithm.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `encryption_algorithm_name` must be one of [ aes, aes128gcm, aes192gcm, aes256gcm ]

hash_algorithm.description: The hash algorithm to use for this P1 encryption item.

dhgroup.description: The Diffie-Hellman (DH) group to use for this P1 encryption item.

prf_algorithm.description: The PRF algorithm to use for this P1 encryption item. This value has no affect unless the P1 entry has PRF enabled.

ikeid.description: The unique IKE ID for this phase 1 entry. This value is dynamically set and cannot be set or changed by users.

descr.description: A description for this IPsec phase 1 entry.

iketype.description: The IKE protocol version this phase 1 entry will use.

mode.description:
The IKEv1 negotiation mode this phase 1 entry will use.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:

protocol.description: The IP version this phase 1 entry will use.

interface.description: The interface for the local endpoint of this phase 1 entry. This should be an interface that is reachable by the remote peer.

remote_gateway.description: The IP address or hostname of the remote gateway.

authentication_method.description: The IPsec authentication method this tunnel will use.

myid_type.description: The identifier type used by the local end of the tunnel.

myid_data.description:
The identifier value used by the local end of the tunnel. This must be a value that corresponds with the current `myid_type` value.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `myid_type` must not be equal to `'myaddress'`

peerid_type.description: The identifier type used by the remote end of the tunnel.

peerid_data.description:
The identifier value used by the remote end of the tunnel. This must be a value that corresponds with the current `peerid_type` value.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `peerid_type` must not be one of [ any, peeraddress ]

pre_shared_key.description:
The Pre-Shared Key (PSK) value. This key must match on both peers and should be long and random to protect the tunnel and its contents. A weak Pre-Shared Key can lead to a tunnel compromise.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `authentication_method` must be equal to `'pre_shared_key'`

certref.description:
The certificate which identifies this system. The certificate must have at least one non-wildcard SAN.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `authentication_method` must be equal to `'cert'`

caref.description:
The certificate authority to use when validating the peer certificate.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `authentication_method` must be equal to `'cert'`

rekey_time.description: The amount of time (in seconds) before an child SA establishes new keys.

reauth_time.description: The amount of time (in seconds) before an child SA is torn down and recreated from scratch, including authentication.

rand_time.description: A random value up to this amount will be subtracted from the `rekey_time` to avoid simultaneous renegotiation.

lifetime.description: The hard child SA lifetime (in seconds) after which the child SA will be expired.

startaction.description: The option used to force specific initiation/responder behavior for child SA (P2) entries.

closeaction.description: The option used to control the behavior when the remote peer unexpectedly closes a child SA (P2)

nat_traversal.description: The option used to enable the use of NAT-T (i.e. the encapsulation of ESP in UDP packets) if needed, which can help with clients that are behind restrictive firewalls.

gw_duplicates.description: Enables or disables the allowance of multiple phase 1 configurations with the same remote gateway endpoint.

mobike.description: Enables or disables the use of MOBIKE for this tunnel.

splitconn.description: Enables or disables the use split connection entries with multiple phase 2 configurations. Required for remote endpoints that support only a single traffic selector per child SA.

prfselect_enable.description: Enables or disables manual Pseudo-Random Function (PRF) selection.

ikeport.description: The UDP port for IKE on the remote gateway. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

nattport.description: The UDP port for NAT-T on the remote gateway. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

dpd_delay.description: The delay (in seconds) between sending peer acknowledgement messages.

dpd_maxfail.description: The number of consecutive failures allowed before disconnecting.

encryption.description: The encryption algorithms supported by this P1 encryption.

name.description: The name of the encryption algorithm to use for this P2 encryption item.

keylen.description:
The key length for the encryption algorithm.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `name` must be one of [ aes, aes128gcm, aes192gcm, aes256gcm ]

uniqid.description: A unique ID used to identify this IPsec phase2 entry internally. This value is automatically set by the system and cannot be changed.

reqid.description: A unique ID used to identify this IPsec phase2 entry internally. This value is automatically set by the system and cannot be changed.

ikeid.description: The `ikeid` of the parent IPsec phase 1 entry this IPsec phase 2 entry belongs to.

descr.description: A description for this IPsec phase 2 entry.

mode.description: The IPsec phase 2 mode this entry will use.

localid_type.description:
The local ID type to use for this phase 2 entry. Valid value options are: an existing interface, `address`, `network`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must not be equal to `'transport'`

localid_address.description:
The local network IP component of this IPsec security association.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `localid_type` must be one of [ address, network ]

localid_netbits.description:
The subnet bits of the `localid_address` network.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `localid_type` must be equal to `'network'`

natlocalid_type.description:
The NAT/BINAT translation type for this IPsec phase 2 entry. Leave as `null` if NAT/BINAT is not needed. Valid value options are: an existing interface, `address`, `network`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must not be one of [ transport, vti ]

natlocalid_address.description:
The NAT/BINAT local network IP component of this IPsec security association.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `natlocalid_type` must be one of [ address, network ]

natlocalid_netbits.description:
The subnet bits of the `natlocalid_address` network.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `natlocalid_type` must be equal to `'network'`

remoteid_type.description:
The remote ID type to use for this phase 2 entry. Valid value options are: `address`, `network`. For interface values, the `:ip` modifier can be appended to the value to use the interface's IP address instead of its entire subnet.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must not be equal to `'transport'`

remoteid_address.description:
The remote network IP component of this IPsec security association.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `remoteid_type` must be one of [ address, network ]

remoteid_netbits.description:
The subnet bits of the `remoteid_address` network.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `remoteid_type` must be equal to `'network'`

protocol.description: the IPsec phase 2 proposal protocol for this entry. Encapsulating Security Payload (`esp`) performs encryption and authentication, Authentication Header (`ah`) is authentication only.

encryption_algorithm_option.description:
The encryption algorithms to be used by this phase 2 entry.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must be equal to `'esp'`

hash_algorithm_option.description: The hashing algorithms used by this IPsec phase 2 entry. Note: Hash is ignored with GCM algorithms. SHA1 provides weak security and should be avoided.

pfsgroup.description: The PFS key group this IPsec phase 2 entry should use. Note: Groups 1, 2, 5, 22, 23, and 24 provide weak security and should be avoided.

rekey_time.description: The amount of time (in seconds) before an IKE SA establishes new keys.

rand_time.description: A random value up to this amount will be subtracted from the `rekey_time` and `reauth_time` to avoid simultaneous renegotiation.

lifetime.description: The hard IKE SA lifetime (in seconds) after which the IKE SA will be expired.

pinghost.description: The IP address to send an ICMP echo request to inside the tunnel. Can trigger initiation of a tunnel mode P2, but does not trigger initiation of a VTI mode P2.

keepalive.description: Enables or disables checking this P2 and initiating if disconnected; does not send traffic inside the tunnel. This check ignores the P1 option 'Child SA Start Action' and works for both VTI and tunnel mode P2s. For IKEv2 without split connections, this only needs to be enabled on one P2.

common_name.description: The X.509 common name for the client certificate, or the username for VPNs utilizing password authentication.

block.description: Enables or disables the client from connecting to this server. Do not use this option to permanently disable a client due to a compromised key or password. Use a CRL instead.

description.description: The description for this client specific override.

server_list.description: The OpenVPN servers that will utilize this override. When no servers are specified, the override will apply to all servers.

tunnel_network.description: The IPv4 virtual network used for private communications between the server and client hosts.

tunnel_networkv6.description: The IPv6 virtual network used for private communications between the server and client hosts.

local_network.description: The IPv4 server-side networks that will be accessible from this particular client.

local_networkv6.description: the IPv6 server-side networks that will be accessible from this particular client.

remote_network.description: The IPv4 client-side networks that will be routed to this client specifically using iroute, so that a site-to-site VPN can be established.

remote_networkv6.description: The IPv6 client-side networks that will be routed to this client specifically using iroute, so that a site-to-site VPN can be established.

gwredir.description: Enable forcing all client-generated traffic through the tunnel.

push_reset.description: Enables or disables preventing this client from receiving any server-defined client settings.

remove_route.description: Enables or disables preventing this client from receiving any server-defined routes without removing any other options.

dns_domain.description: The default domain to provide to the client.

dns_server1.description: The primary DNS server to provide to the client.

dns_server2.description: The secondary DNS server to provide to the client.

dns_server3.description: The tertiary DNS server to provide to the client.

dns_server4.description: The quaternary DNS server to provide to the client.

ntp_server1.description: The primary NTP server to provide to the client.

ntp_server2.description: The secondary NTP server to provide to the client.

netbios_enable.description: Enables or disables NetBIOS over TCP/IP.

netbios_ntype.description:
The NetBIOS node type.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

netbios_scope.description:
The NetBIOS Scope ID. This provides an extended naming service for NetBIOS over TCP/IP. The NetBIOS scope ID isolates NetBIOS traffic on a single network to only those nodes with the same NetBIOS scope ID.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

wins_server1.description:
The primary WINS server to provide to the client.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

wins_server2.description:
The secondary WINS server to provide to the client.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

custom_options.description: Additional OpenVPN options to add for this client.

vpnid.description: The unique ID for this OpenVPN client. This value is assigned by the system and cannot be changed.

vpnif.description: The VPN interface name for this OpenVPN client. This value is assigned by the system and cannot be changed.

description.description: The description for this OpenVPN client.

dev_mode.description: The carrier mode for this OpenVPN client. `tun` mode carries IPv4 and IPv6 (layer 3) and is the most common and compatible mode across all platforms. `tap` mode is capable of carrying 802.3 (layer 2).

protocol.description: The protocol used by this OpenVPN client.

interface.description:
The interface used by the firewall to originate this OpenVPN client connection.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `protocol` must not be one of [ UDP, TCP ]

server_addr.description: The IP address or hostname of the OpenVPN server this client will connect to.

server_port.description: The port used by the server to receive client connections. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

local_port.description: The port binding used by OpenVPN for client connections. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

proxy_addr.description: The address for an HTTP Proxy this client can use to connect to a remote server.

proxy_port.description: The port used by the HTTP Proxy. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

proxy_authtype.description: The type of authentication used by the proxy server.

proxy_user.description:
The username to use for authentication to the remote proxy.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `proxy_authtype` must not be equal to `'none'`

proxy_passwd.description:
The username to use for authentication to the remote proxy.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `proxy_authtype` must not be equal to `'none'`

auth_user.description: The username used to authenticate with the OpenVPN server.

auth_pass.description:
The password used to authenticate with the OpenVPN server.

auth_retry_none.description: Disables retrying authentication if an authentication failed error is received from the server

tls.description: The TLS key this OpenVPN client will use to sign control channel packets with an HMAC signature for authentication when establishing the tunnel.

tls_type.description:
The TLS key usage type. In `auth` mode, the TLS key is used only as HMAC authentication for the control channel, protecting the peers from unauthorized connections. The `crypt` mode encrypts the control channel communication in addition to providing authentication, providing more privacy and traffic control channel obfuscation.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `tls` must not be equal to `NULL`

tlsauth_keydir.description:
The TLS key direction. This must be set to complementary values on the client and client. For example, if the client is set to 0, the client must be set to 1. Both may be set to omit the direction, in which case the TLS Key will be used bidirectionally.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `tls` must not be equal to `NULL`

caref.description: The `refid` of the CA object to assume as the peer CA.

certref.description: The `refid` of the certificate object to assume as the OpenVPN client certificate.

data_ciphers.description: The encryption algorithms/ciphers allowed by this OpenVPN client.

data_ciphers_fallback.description: The fallback encryption algorithm/cipher used for data channel packets when communicating with clients that do not support data encryption algorithm negotiation (e.g. Shared Key).

digest.description: The algorithm used to authenticate data channel packets, and control channel packets if a TLS Key is present.

remote_cert_tls.description: Enables or disables requiring hosts to have a client certificate to connect.

tunnel_network.description: The IPv4 virtual network used for private communications between this client and client hosts.

tunnel_networkv6.description: The IPv6 virtual network used for private communications between this client and client hosts.

remote_network.description: IPv4 networks that will be routed through the tunnel, so that a site-to-site VPN can be established without manually changing the routing tables. Expressed as a list of one or more CIDR ranges or host/network type aliases. If this is a site-to-site VPN, enter the remote LAN/s here. May be left empty for non site-to-site VPN.

remote_networkv6.description: IPv6 networks that will be routed through the tunnel, so that a site-to-site VPN can be established without manually changing the routing tables. Expressed as a list of one or more CIDR ranges or host/network type aliases. If this is a site-to-site VPN, enter the remote LAN/s here. May be left empty for non site-to-site VPN.

use_shaper.description: Maximum outgoing bandwidth (in bytes per second) for this tunnel. Use `null` no limit.

allow_compression.description: The compression mode allowed by this OpenVPN client. Compression can potentially increase throughput but may allow an attacker to extract secrets if they can control compressed plaintext traversing the VPN (e.g. HTTP)

passtos.description: Enables or disables setting the TOS IP header value of tunnel packets to match the encapsulated packet value.

route_no_pull.description: Enables or disables the servers ability to add routes to the client's routing table.

route_no_exec.description: Enables or disables adding/removing routes automatically.

dns_add.description: Enables or disables using the DNS server(s) provided by the OpenVPN server.

topology.description:
The method used to supply a virtual adapter IP address to clients when using TUN mode on IPv4.

inactive_seconds.description: The amount of time (in seconds) until a client connection is closed for inactivity.

ping_method.description: The method used to define ping configuration.

keepalive_interval.description:
The keepalive interval parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:

keepalive_timeout.description:
The keepalive timeout parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'keepalive'`

ping_seconds.description:
The number of seconds to accept no packets before sending a ping to the remote peer over the TCP/UDP control channel.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

ping_action.description:
The action to take after a ping to the remote peer times-out.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:

The number of seconds that must elapse before the ping is considered a timeout and the configured `ping_action` is performed.

custom_options.description: Additional options to add to the OpenVPN client configuration.

udp_fast_io.description: Enables or disables fast I/O operations with UDP writes to tun/tap (Experimental).

sndrcvbuf.description: The send and receive buffer size for OpenVPN. Set to null to use the system default.

authmode.description:

dev_mode.description: The carrier mode for this OpenVPN server. `tun` mode carries IPv4 and IPv6 (layer 3) and is the most common and compatible mode across all platforms. `tap` mode is capable of carrying 802.3 (layer 2).

protocol.description: The protocol used by this OpenVPN server.

interface.description:
The interface or Virtual IP address where OpenVPN will receive client connections.

local_port.description: The port used by OpenVPN to receive client connections. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

tls_type.description:
The TLS key usage type. In `auth` mode, the TLS key is used only as HMAC authentication for the control channel, protecting the peers from unauthorized connections. The `crypt` mode encrypts the control channel communication in addition to providing authentication, providing more privacy and traffic control channel obfuscation.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:

tlsauth_keydir.description:
The TLS key direction. This must be set to complementary values on the client and server. For example, if the server is set to 0, the client must be set to 1. Both may be set to omit the direction, in which case the TLS Key will be used bidirectionally.

caref.description: The `refid` of the CA object to assume as the peer CA.

certref.description: The `refid` of the certificate object to assume as the OpenVPN server certificate.

dh_length.description: The Diffie-Hellman (DH) parameter set used for key exchange.

data_ciphers.description: The encryption algorithms/ciphers allowed by this OpenVPN server.

data_ciphers_fallback.description: The fallback encryption algorithm/cipher used for data channel packets when communicating with clients that do not support data encryption algorithm negotiation (e.g. Shared Key).

digest.description: The algorithm used to authenticate data channel packets, and control channel packets if a TLS Key is present.

strictusercn.description:

Expressed as a list of one or more CIDR ranges or host/network type aliases. If this is a site-to-site VPN, enter the remote LAN/s here. May be left empty for non site-to-site VPN.

maxclients.description: The maximum number of clients allowed to concurrently connect to this server.

allow_compression.description: The compression mode allowed by this OpenVPN server. Compression can potentially increase throughput but may allow an attacker to extract secrets if they can control compressed plaintext traversing the VPN (e.g. HTTP)

passtos.description: Enables or disables setting the TOS IP header value of tunnel packets to match the encapsulated packet value.

client2client.description: Enables or disables allowing communication between clients connected to this server.

duplicate_cn.description: Enables or disable allowing the same user to connect multiple times.

connlimit.description:
The number of concurrent connections a single user can have.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `duplicate_cn` must be equal to `true`

dynamic_ip.description: Enables or disables allowing connected clients to retain their connections if their IP address changes.

topology.description:
The method used to supply a virtual adapter IP address to clients when using TUN mode on IPv4.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `dev_mode` must be equal to `'tun'`

inactive_seconds.description: The amount of time (in seconds) until a client connection is closed for inactivity.

ping_method.description: The method used to define ping configuration.

keepalive_interval.description:
The keepalive interval parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'keepalive'`

keepalive_timeout.description:
The keepalive timeout parameter.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'keepalive'`

ping_seconds.description:
The number of seconds to accept no packets before sending a ping to the remote peer over the TCP/UDP control channel.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

ping_push.description:
Enables or disables push ping to the VPN client.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

ping_action.description:
The action to take after a ping to the remote peer times-out.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

ping_action_seconds.description:
The number of seconds that must elapse before the ping is considered a timeout and the configured `ping_action` is performed.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

ping_action_push.description:
Enables or disables pushing the ping action to the VPN client.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `ping_method` must be equal to `'ping'`

dns_domain.description:
The default domain to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

dns_server1.description:
The primary DNS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

dns_server2.description:
The secondary DNS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

dns_server3.description:
The tertiary DNS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

dns_server4.description:
The quaternary DNS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

push_blockoutsidedns.description:
Enables or disables blocking Windows 10 clients' access to DNS servers except across OpenVPN while connected, forcing clients to use only VPN DNS servers.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

push_register_dns.description:
Enables or disables running `net stop dnscache`, `net start dnscache`, `ipconfig /flushdns` and `ipconfig /registerdns` on connection initiation for Windows clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

ntp_server1.description:
The primary NTP server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

ntp_server2.description:
The secondary NTP server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

netbios_enable.description:
Enables or disables NetBIOS over TCP/IP.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

netbios_ntype.description:
The NetBIOS node type.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

netbios_scope.description:
The NetBIOS Scope ID. This provides an extended naming service for NetBIOS over TCP/IP. The NetBIOS scope ID isolates NetBIOS traffic on a single network to only those nodes with the same NetBIOS scope ID.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `netbios_enable` must be equal to `true`

wins_server1.description:
The primary WINS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

wins_server2.description:
The secondary WINS server to provide to clients.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

custom_options.description: Additional options to add to the OpenVPN server configuration.

username_as_common_name.description:
Enables or disable the username of the client being used in place of the certificate common name for purposes such as determining Client Specific Overrides.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `mode` must be one of [ server_user, server_tls_user ]

sndrcvbuf.description: The send and receive buffer size for OpenVPN. Set to null to use the system default.

create_gw.description: The gateway type(s) that will be created when a virtual interface is assigned to this OpenVPN server

applied.description: Displays `true` when all WireGuard changes are applied and there are no pending changes left.Displays `false` when there are pending WireGuard changes that have not been applied.

address.description: The IPv4 or IPv6 address for this peer IP.

mask.description: The subnet mask for this peer IP.

descr.description: A description for this allowed peer IP.

enabled.description: Enables or disables this WireGuard peer.

tun.description: The WireGuard tunnel for this peer.

endpoint.description: The IP address or hostname of the remote peer. Set to `null` to make this a dynamic endpoint.

port.description:
The port used by the remote peer. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `endpoint` must not be equal to `NULL`

descr.description: The description for this peer.

persistentkeepalive.description: The interval (in seconds) for Keep Alive packets sent to this peer. Set to `null` to disable.

publickey.description: The public key for this peer.

presharedkey.description: The pre-shared key for this tunnel.

allowedips.description: The allowed IP/subnets for this WireGuard peer.

enable.description: Enables or disables WireGuard on this system. WireGuard cannot be disabled when one or more tunnels is assigned to a pfSense interface.

keep_conf.description: Enables or disables keeping the WireGuard configuration when the package is uninstalled/reinstalled.

resolve_interval_track.description: Enables or disables tracking the 'Aliases Hostnames Resolve Interval' value as the `resolve_internal` value instead of specifying a value directly.

resolve_interval.description:
The interval (in seconds) for re-resolving endpoint host/domain names.

This field is only available when the following conditions are met:
- `resolve_interval_track` must be equal to `false`

interface_group.description: Configures which WireGuard tunnels are members of the WireGuard interface group.

hide_secrets.description: Enables or disables hiding all secrets (private and pre-shared keys) in the user interface.

hide_peers.description: Enables or disables initially hiding all peers in the user interface.

address.description: The IPv4 or IPv6 address for this WireGuard tunnel.

mask.description: The subnet mask for this WireGuard tunnel.

descr.description: A description for this WireGuard tunnel address entry.

name.description: The name of the WireGuard interface. This value is automatically assigned by the system and cannot be changed.

enabled.description: Enables or disables this tunnels and any associated peers.

listenport.description: The port WireGuard will listen on for this tunnel. Valid options are: a TCP/UDP port number

publickey.description: The public key for this tunnel. This value is automatically derived from the `privatekey` value and cannot be set manually.

privatekey.description: The private key for this tunnel.

mtu.description: The MTU for this WireGuard tunnel interface. This value is ignored if this tunnel is assigned as a pfSense interface.

addresses.description: The IPv4 or IPv6 addresses to assign this WireGuard tunnel interface. This field is ignored if this tunnel interface is assigned to an existing pfSense interface object.

Note: This does not define an actual parameter, rather it allows for any arbitrary query parameters to be included in the request.
